On the ground, enforcement grew harsher and more arbitrary. In Oregon, ICE agents broke the window of a 17\uc0\u8209 year\u8209 old U.S. citizen\'92s car during his lunch break at school, detained him despite his protests of citizenship, and later sought to charge him with \'93interference or obstruction of investigation.\'94 In Texas, agents detained Maher Tarabishi, a 62\u8209 year\u8209 old father and primary caregiver for a son with a rare disease, labeling him a \'93criminal alien\'94 and alleged member of a terrorist organization despite his lack of criminal record. In Massachusetts, Bruna Ferreira, a Brazilian mother of a U.S. citizen child, was arrested for overstaying a tourist visa and sent to a distant detention facility. In Seattle, ICE officers detained Native American actor Elaine Miles after declaring her tribal ID \'93fake,\'94 ignoring her offer to verify it with her tribe. ProPublica reported that ICE has detained more than 600 immigrant children this year, many separated from their families after traffic stops and held in shelters for extended periods. These cases show a system that treats legal status as fragile, family ties as irrelevant, and racial profiling as routine.\
\
The president\'92s own words reinforced this hierarchy. In a Thanksgiving message that devolved into a rant, Trump threatened to strip citizenship from naturalized Americans he deemed \'93non\uc0\u8209 compatible with Western civilization.\'94 He did not define the term, but the context made clear that he meant immigrants and communities of color he associates with political opposition. In Washington, the administration\'92s handling of an Afghan asylum seeker accused of shooting two National Guard members became a political weapon. Kristi Noem confirmed that DHS had granted him asylum in April after vetting by the CIA and the National Counterterrorism Center, but FBI Director Kash Patel deflected responsibility. The incident was used to argue that vetting had been lax and to justify the broader clampdown on Afghan and other asylum cases. Citizenship and refuge, in this framework, are not stable legal statuses. They are contingent favors that can be revoked when politically useful.\
\
The sixth development was the deliberate reshaping of the information environment. The administration canceled the release of the third\uc0\u8209 quarter GDP advanced estimate, a standard economic report, days after Trump\'92s \'93crypto czar\'94 touted the economy\'92s reliance on AI investments. With inflation near 10 percent year\u8209 over\u8209 year and consumer confidence at historic lows, the decision looked less like a technical delay and more like an effort to hide bad news. At the same time, Health and Human Services Secretary Robert F. Kennedy Jr. admitted that he had ordered the CDC to change its website language on vaccines and autism, despite scientific consensus that vaccines do not cause autism and a prior promise to a senator not to alter that statement. The site now carries a note about his broken promise. These acts show how economic and health data can be massaged or suppressed to manage perception rather than inform the public.\
