The seventh development concerned elections and representation. Trump intensified his campaign to redraw congressional maps mid\uc0\u8209 decade. In Indiana, he pressured the state Senate to take up redistricting within two weeks, promising political support for those who complied and primary challenges against those who did not. Lawmakers who resisted found themselves targeted by swatting incidents\'97false emergency calls that brought armed police to their homes. In Texas, a federal court blocked new maps that would have created five more Republican\u8209 leaning districts, but the Supreme Court agreed to review the decision, leaving the outcome uncertain. California responded by advancing and approving a ballot measure to add five Democrat\u8209 friendly districts of its own, explicitly as a counterweight to Texas. In North Carolina, the state Board of Elections, now under Republican control, voted along party lines to share voter data with the federal SAVE immigration database, raising fears that naturalized citizens and eligible voters could be swept into scrutiny and deterred from participating. Trump called for the release of Tina Peters, a convicted county clerk who had breached election equipment, casting her as a martyr for \'93exposing fraud.\'94 The Justice Department\'92s voting section, now aligned with his agenda, backed Texas\'92s maps and opposed California\'92s. The language of \'93election integrity\'94 is being used to justify both suppression and impunity.\
