Against this backdrop, there were pockets of institutional resistance. A federal appeals court upheld nearly $1 million in sanctions against Trump and his lawyer Alina Habba for a frivolous racketeering suit against Hillary Clinton, the DNC, and James Comey, noting a \'93pattern\'94 of meritless litigation. Another federal appeals court blocked the administration\'92s attempt to expand rapid deportation for immigrants believed to have been in the country less than two years, citing due process concerns. A federal judge dismissed the criminal cases against Comey and New York Attorney General Letitia James, ruling that the interim U.S. attorney who brought them had been unlawfully appointed, and thus had no authority to indict. Judges ordered the Justice Department to expedite FOIA processing on Epstein\uc0\u8209 related records and sought to unseal grand jury materials and investigative files. The Florida Supreme Court ruled that Marsy\'92s Law does not automatically grant anonymity to police officers involved in fatal incidents, limiting a tactic that had shielded officers from public scrutiny. A federal court blocked Texas\'92s new congressional maps, at least for now. These decisions show that parts of the judiciary still see themselves as limits on power, not its servants.\
