Civil society also showed its capacity to resist. In North Carolina, masked Border Patrol operations under \'93Operation Charlotte\'92s Web\'94 sparked protests, mutual aid, and legal support. Communities organized food deliveries for those afraid to leave their homes, and students and activists in Charlotte, Durham, and Raleigh held peaceful demonstrations. The Border Patrol withdrew its agents earlier than planned, a rare retreat in the face of local opposition. Across the country, campaigns like \'93We Ain\'92t Buying It\'94 urged consumers to boycott Amazon, Target, and Home Depot over their ties to ICE operations, and to divest from private prison companies GEO Group and CoreCivic. Protesters staged \'93Tesla Takedowns\'94 at dealerships, urging people not to buy the cars because of Elon Musk\'92s political spending. In Chicago, faith leaders sued DHS over being barred from ministering to detained immigrants, framing the issue as a First Amendment violation. These efforts did not change federal policy in the week at hand, but they did impose costs, draw attention, and show that organized resistance can still force adjustments at the margins.\
