There were also signs that voters themselves may be shifting. Republican lawmakers expressed open worry about the 2026 midterms after poor off\uc0\u8209 year results, rising health insurance premiums, and a president whose approval had fallen to 41.9 percent with 55.7 percent disapproval. A new Emerson poll showed Democrats within two points of Republicans in Tennessee\'92s deeply conservative 7th congressional district, which Trump had once carried by more than 20 points. In Tennessee, more than half of surveyed Americans said they would avoid buying a Tesla for political reasons. These are not yet structural changes in power, but they hint at a public that is not fully aligned with the project of executive aggrandizement.\
\
Looking ahead, several scheduled or pending decisions will test whether the remaining guardrails hold. The Supreme Court\'92s review of the Texas redistricting case will shape not only that state\'92s maps but the permissibility of mid\uc0\u8209 decade partisan remapping nationwide. The Pentagon\'92s investigation into Senator Kelly and the Navy\'92s report to Secretary Hegseth, due in early December, will show whether the military is willing to discipline a sitting senator for restating the law on unlawful orders. The North Carolina House Oversight Committee\'92s hearing on the Chapel Hill school district, set for early December, will reveal how far state lawmakers will go in enforcing anti\u8209 trans and anti\u8209 DEI laws against local educators. The Justice Department\'92s efforts to unseal Epstein materials and respond to FOIA orders will either reinforce or erode public trust in its willingness to expose elite wrongdoing. And the administration\'92s promised cancellation of Biden\'92s autopen\u8209 signed orders will likely face court challenges that will clarify how far a president can go in rewriting the legal past.\
\
In the larger arc of the term, Week 45 matters because it shows a regime settling into its methods. Executive power is exercised through emergency declarations, legal opinions that stretch old doctrines, and symbolic orders that rewrite memory. Law enforcement is purged, repopulated with loyalists, and turned against opponents. Immigration and citizenship are used to sort people into those who belong and those who can be removed. Information is managed, whether by canceling economic reports, editing scientific websites, or purging library shelves. Yet courts still sometimes say no, states still sue, communities still protest, and voters still shift. The Democracy Clock remains at 8:01 p.m. because these countervailing forces have not yet been broken. But the week\'92s deepening of traits like unchecked executive power, law as weapon, politicized civil service, and stratified citizenship shows how fragile that equilibrium is. The hands did not move, but the weight on one side of the scale grew heavier.\
